{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/00414211057/1958041101/0077.xml":{"full_text":"Recession Farm Led and Farm Fed\nPeople Want Jobs, Not\nCharily; Says Mansfield\nSpeaking at a Jackson-Jefferson day dinner in Helena Mon\nday evening,Montana's Junior Senator Mike Mansfield talked\nabout the recession, farm prices and foreign policy in what he\ncalled a report to his constituents who \"can tear me down if I\ndon't fulfill the expectations you have for me\". He added, \"you\nmade me what I am today\", and said he needed to be refreshed\nand had come home to\nwhat has not been done and\nwhat should be done.\nMansfield, who is majority whip in\nthe Senate, said this recession, like\nothers in history is farm led and farm\nbred and steps must be taken to keep\nit from developing into a depression.\nHe said he was for 90% of parity\nand he did not know if it was going\nto be possible to override the Presi\ndent's veto of the farm price freeze\nbill. At the time of the Easter recess\nhe said they were two votes short of\nbeing able to override. He thought\nperhaps by the time the senators had\nbeen home for a few days some of\nthem might change their minds. \"If\nit is possible\", he said, \"we will over\nride the veto\",\nMansfield pointed out legislation\nsupported by the Democrats to allevi\nate the recession included the high\nway building program, forest roads,\naccess roads, the Lewis Clark high\nway, loans for housing on a reason\nable basis, the Community Facilities\nbill, and extension of unemployment\ncompensation. He said this was all\n\"meritorious legislation\".\nHe said the President didn't know\nwhere to go on the serious problems\nfacing the nation, and that Eisen\nhower's \"chins up and eyes front\"\nslogan didn't mean anything because\n\"we are not in the Army\".\nMansfield declared the American\npeople wanted jobs not charity.\nIn the field of foreign policy he\nsaid we have suffered many humiliat\ning defeats. He said NATO is steadily\ndisintegrating and we are spending\nour sustenance on something that has\noutlived its usefulness.\nAbout national defense he sug\ngested the number of generals and\nadmirals in Washington be cut in\nhalf, as well as the undersecretaries,\nand he would not give more control\nto the Secretary of Defense, \"no\nmatter whether he were Democrat\nor Republican\". Mansfield stressed\nDemo Highway\nGroup To Meet\nIn Capital City\nA regional hearing of the Demo\ncratic Advisory Committee on High\nways and Highway financing will be\nheld in Helena at the Placer Hotel on\nMonday, April 14 at 1:00 p.m., accord\ning to Nels Bach, Sidney, former\nmember of the Highway Commission\nand chairman of the Advisory Com\nmittee,\nThe committee has been investigat\ning means of speeding up Montana's\nroad program and considering various\nmethods of financing highway con\nstruction and maintenance.\nThe Advisory Committee meetings\nare non-political in nature and have\nbeen attended by mayors, county com\nmissioners, Good Roads Associations,\nfarm groups, labor groups, chambers\nof commerce, trucking associations,\nstockgrowers and other interested\npersons. All meetings are public.\nPresent members of the Advisory\nCommittee are: Don McKinnon, for\nmer state highway engineer, vice\nchairman; Representative Lloyd J.\nMichels, chairman of the House High\nways and Highway Transportation\nCommittee; Representative James\nWood, Jr., Loma, member of that\ncommittee; Sen. Charles A. Bovey,\nchairman of the Senate Highways\nand Transportation Committee; Arn\nold Olsen, Democratic gubernatorial\ncandidate in 1956; Joe Crosswhite,\nColumbia Falls, business representa\ntive of the Operating Engineers un\nion; Randall Swanberg, Great Falls\nattorney; Ole Gunderson, Power,\nformer member of the House of Rep\nresentatives; Lester Rutledge, treas\nurer of the Democratic State Central\nCommittee, and Big Sandy rancher.\nlearn#\u00bb-\u2014\nthe need to see that control of the\nfinancial destiny of the country stay\nin the hands of civilians.\nBankruptcy\n(Continued From Page One)\nsupports will mean additional finan\ncial hardships for the producers and\nthe economy a^ a whole.\n\"Consumer* will not benefit by\nthe farm price cuts enforced in\nWashington. Experience in recent\nyears is that while farmer-received\nprices have been declining, consum\ner prices have been climbing higher\nand higher.\n\"The tragedy of the situation,\"\nKenfield said, \"is that there is no Ad\nministration effort to decrease gov\nernment aids to the steel makers, the\nrailroads, the bankers, the private\npower companies, the big commercial\npublishers, and many other big busi\nness elements with whom the farmer\nmust deal.\nRather than relieving farmers\nfrom 'enforced stagnation', as the\nPresident says, his policies are driv\ning them to it. In a recent Eisenhower\nyear, more than 1,800,000 farm peo\n\nP^ e drifted to the cities in one of the\ngreatest mass migrations in our na\ntion s history. Meanwhile unemploy\nin the cities soared to\nmore\nthan 5,000,000 plus several millions\nmore unemployed part-time, which\nis the largest number of U.S. jobless\nsince the early 1940's.\n\"As to the 'controls' of which the\nPresident complained in his veto\nmessage, it must be said that bank\nruptcy resulting from low income is\nitself a pretty rigid control. Most\nfarmers I know are willing to accept\nregulation of production and market\ning if they have assurance of full\nparity prices on what they do produce.\nIt is ironic that President Eisenhower\nand his Secretary of Agriculture\nthemselves stiffened up the 'controls'\nwhen they removed several years ago\nmuch of the democratic authority of\nthe elected local and county farmer\ncommittees.\nI\nN.D. Republicans Nominate\nPower Company Official In\nMove To Defeat Langer\nWASHINGTON, D. C|\u2014(NRECA)\n\u2014North Dakota power companies\nhave unsuccessfully fought to push\nSen. William Langer out of public\noffice for over a quarter of a cen\ntury. Evidently tired of the feat, this\nyear they have selected one of their\nown fraternity to oppose the 18-year\nSenate veteran, considered one of the\nbest friends the rural electrification\nprogram has in Congress.\nThe North Dakota Republican State\nCentral Committee last week by\npassed Langer and endorsed Clyde\nDuffy, a member of the board of di\nrectors of the Otter Tail Power Co.,\nfor the United States Senate. Langer\nwill oppose Duffy in the state pri\nmaries in June.\nLanger faced a similar situation in\n1952 when the Republican State Cen\ntral Committee endorsed Fred Aan\ndahl, presently Assistant Secretary of\nInterior, for the Senate. Langer\ntrounced Aandahl in the primary.\nThe population of North Dakota\nin the 1950 census was 619,636. Ap\nproximately 50% of North Dakotans\nare engaged in agriculture.\nDuffy, in addition to being a di\nrector of Otter Tail Power Co., is a\nsuccessful lawyer and banker. He is\n68 years old, three years younger than\nLanger. According to Moody's Public\nUtilities Manual, none of the principal\nholders of Common stock in Otter\nTail resides in North Dakota.\nNational Rural Electric Co-op As\nsociation .voting record compilations\nindicate that Langer leads all Senate\nRepublicans in support for the rural\nelectrification and related federal\npower programs.\nAre YOU Registered\nTo Vote?\nRemember, April 18\nIs final day to\nregister for\nJune 3 Primary.\nUnder Benson\n6 a.m. To Midnight\nJobs Help Farmer and\nWife Stay On Land\nSenator James E. Murray has cited\nto the Senate one of the Department\nof Agriculture's \"glowing examples\nof an achievement of its Rural Devel\nopment Program for family farmers\nas cause for firing Secretary of Agri\nculture Benson \"by sundown\".\nReading from a USDA publication,\nExtension Service Review, Murray\nquoted this example of how the pro\ngram for family farmers works. The\nmagazine said;\n\"Farm people in the county (Choc\ntow county, Oklahoma) were quoick\nto take advantage of the opportuni\nties provided through the Rural De\nvelopment Program. Floyd Berry and\nwife are good examples. Berry oper\nates a 280-acre farm and has a small\ngrade A dairy and a commercial beef\nherd. To supplement farm income Mrs.\nBerry drew on her experience as a\nhousewife to get a job cooking in a\nlocal cafe. She works from 6 a.m. to\n2 p.m. daily. Her husband is working\nat a filling station from 3 p.m. until\nmidnight.\n\"Berry handles the farm chores in\nthe morning and his wife takes over\nafternoons\nSenator Murray then commented:\n\"This, then, is the formula for suc\nI\ncessful farming under Benson. Get\nyour wife a full-time job in town.\nGet yourself a full-time job in town.\n\"If you are lucky, the husband's\nin-town wages will pay the losses re\nsulting from farming under Benson\nand you will still have your wife's\npay as a fry-cook to buy some grocer\nies and clothing.\n\"This glowing example of the oper\nations and achievements of one of Mr.\nBenson's programs simply reinforces\nmy own conviction that he should be\nfired before sundown\u2014a conviction\nI have had for the last 1,896 days,\nwhich goes back to the day after his\nappointment.\n\nLandowners\nPlan Statewide\nOrganization\nThe Lower Yellowstone Protective\nAssociation has scheduled a state\nwide meeting to be held at the Labor\nTemple, April 12, 1958, located at\n24 South 29th Street, Billings. This\nmeeting is being called for the pur\npose of discussing interstate highway\nrouting, and to take preliminary steps\ntoward state-wide organization, ac\ncording to J. O. Wold, Jr., Laurel,\nassociation president.\nThe Lower Yellowstone Valley As\nsociation, representing a group of\nlandowners, was organized to protest\nrouting the Interstate Highway\nthrough irrigated bottomland in the\nYellowstone Valley. The group wants\nthe road to cross less-productive lands\nnorth of the valley rim. The choice\nfarm lands are a valuable part of the\nheritage of future generations. Also\nthere is a tremendous saving to the\nstate's taxpayers from less expensive\nright-of-ways, and far less mainte\nnance costs in following years, which\nis the sole obligation of the state,\nwithout the benefit of federal aid.\nUnited States congressmen, repre\nsentatives, Governor Aronson, farm\nassociation leaders, the press, and the\ngeneral public have been invited. Rep.\nLeRoy Anderson has affirmed that\nhe will attend. It is expected that\nmany of the others will also be in\nattendance.\nDemands from over the state war\nrant a state-wide organization to pro\ntect irrigated valleys, and a better\nlook into the entire highway situation.\nPaul Smith Files For Reelection\nTo Public Service Commission\nPaul T. Smith, 54, present chair\nman of the Montana Railroad and\nPublic Service Commission, Monday\nfiled his nominating petition for re\nelection to a six-year term with that\nagency. He is a Democrat.\nIn his petition, Smith pledged \"my\ncontinued efforts for intelligent regu\nlation of utilities and transportation\nto give the people of Montana good\nservice at a fair cost and allow con\ntinued growth and progress in our\nstate.\nyy\nm\nWm\nI\nSmith was first elected in 1938\nand served continuously until Janu\nary 6, 1953. In October, 1954, he\nwas nominated by the Democratic\nparty in a special convention as its\ncandidate for a four-year unexpired\nterm. In the general election, Smith\ndefeated the Republican candidate\nwho had been appointed to the post\nby Governor J. Hugo Aronson fol\nMSC Enrollment Eor\nSpring Quarter 3100\nBOZEMAN\u2014There are 3,100 stu\ndents enrolled at Montana State Col\nlege for the spring quarter, or a 10.2\nper cent increase over the same\nquarter in 1957, a preliminary report\nby Registrar Martha Hawksworth re\nveals.\n\"This means that the increase for\nthe entire year hasJield steady,\" says\nMiss Hawksworth. And the MSC reg\nistrar expects approximately 80 more\nstudents to register this quarter.\nOf the 3,100 students enrolled at\nthe institution, 86 are new registrants.\nForty-three of the 86 are former stu\ndents returning to the campus while\nthere are 43 new students.\nOf the five divisions at Montana\nState, engineering continues to have\nthe largest enrollment. The report\nshows that there are 1,192 students\nin engineering, 740 in the division of\nscience, 426 in household and applied\narts, 381 in the division of education\nand 361 in the division of agriculture.\nAs usual, the freshman class is the\nlargest. The report shows that there\nare 989 freshmen, 838 sophomores,\n679 juniors, and 524 seniors. There\nare 172 graduate students at MSC,\nbringing the total to 3,100.\nThere are 675 veterans enrolled\nfor the spring quarter. This contrasts\nto immediately after the war when\nex-servicemen made up a large per\ncentage of the student body.\nDEMAND THE UNION LABEL\nIf is better to have insurance\nand not need it, than to\nneed it and not have it\nSee Our Agent\nIn Your Community\nMONTANA FARMERS ONION\nMUTUAL FIRE INSURANCE\nGreat Falls, Mont.\nBox 2089\nMontana Farmer* Union\nInsurance Agency\nlowing the resignation of John E.\nHenry.\nSmith was not a member of the\nCommission during 1953 and 1954\nwhen the controversial utility rate\ncases were decided, granting increases\nto the Mountain States Telephone\nTelegraph Company, the Montana\nPower Company and the Montana\nDakota Utilities Company,\nA lifelong Montanan, Smith was\nborn on his family's ranch in the\nBoulder Valley in 1904, the son of\nCon Smith and the former Sarah\nMaquire. His father, a prominent\nMontana pioneer, arrived in Virginia\nCity in 1863.\nDuring his years on the Commis\nsion, Smith has been active in opposi\ntion to freight rate increases. He has\nappeared several times before the\nInterstate Commerce Commission in\nWashington, D. C., in protest to higher\nrates. He also represented the Mon\ntana Commission at the 1955 hearing\nin Phoenix, Ariz., which resulted in\nrate reductions averaging 25 per cent\non interstate rail movements into\nMontana.\n\"I will continue to work diligently\nfor more equitable freight rates for\nMontana,\" he stated.\nAs Commission chairman, Smith\nwas instrumental in establishing the\nsplit-hearing procedure in the major\nrate cases heard recently. Spokesmen\nfor groups opposing the proposed in\ncreases praised this move, saying it\nenabled them a better opportunity to\npresent their case.\n\"Utility rate cases affect the pock\netbooks of practically all Montanans,\nSmith said, \"and every effort must\nbe made to fully protect the interests\nof the people. I believe that public\nutilities are entitled to receive what\nthe courts have held to be a fair re\nturn upon their investment and it is\nI\nthe Commission's duty to allow that\nreturn in all rate cases. However, no\ncompany, no matter how large, should\nbe permitted to charge one cent more\nthan the law allows. These rate cases\nmust be given the fullest possible\nscrutiny so the Commission can fix\nrates which will be fair to the custo\nmers and fair to the utility.\n\nIn 1957, Smith initiated\na move\naimed at reducing the price of gaso\nline in Montana. He appeared before\na legislative committee with a re\nquest for funds to finance an investi\ngation of gas prices by the Commis\nsion. This proposals was studied by\nthe Legislature but no action was\ntaken before the close of the 1957\nsession. \"I will continue my efforts to\nobtain fair gasoline prices for the\npeople of Montana,\" Smith said.\nGovernment Gains $1,\u2014\n(Continued From Page One)\nciation, noted that Agriculture Secre\ntary Ezra Benson's order, effective\ntwo days earlier, will save the gov\nernment 19c per 100 pounds on the\n5 of U. S. milk output it buys,\n\"In contrast, the nation's dairy\nfarmers will lose on their entire pro\nduction about $210 million,\" he said.\nBenson cut supports on manufac\ntured milk products from $3.25 to\n$3.06 per 100 pounds, April 1. Winn\nsaid he expected dairy farmers to\nexpand their output in an effort to\nmake up for their lost income.\n\"There's no evidence that lower\nfarm prices have been translated into\ngreater sales,\" he said. \"Per capita\nsales of all dairy products, in milk\nequivalent, were at a record low in\n1957.\"","height":"20043","width":"13953"}}
